Question: Do you consider Amazon a friend or foe of movie
theaters? Gotta be a friend, right? For most of this year, Prime Video and =
its studio division have been positioning themselves as a savior of sorts t=
o the theatrical industry, with plans to release dozens of big-budget movie=
s in cinemas over the next few years. Amazon certainly pitches its theater =
plans when it=E2=80=99s trying to lure projects from Netflix and other buye=
rs. And if you talk to theater executives, they=E2=80=99re counting on Amaz=
on=E2=80=99s ambitions to compensate for pullbacks
elsewhere, particularly in non-=E2=80=9Cevent=E2=80=9D films.

=C2=A0

But, man, Amazon is a huge question mark, one whose motives and ambitions w=
ill be a driving narrative of the movie business in 2025. Consider what=E2=
=80=99s going on with Red One. Amazon MGM Studios has been jumping up and d=
own to declare the Dwayne Johnson-Chris Evans holiday movie the most viewed=
 in the history of
Prime Video. Not mentioned in those press releases: The $250 million Santa =
kidnapping extravaganza landed on the service just 27 days after a theatric=
al debut that was buoyed by a massive, $100 million marketing campaign. Tha=
t=E2=80=99s a dream for a film studio, which can reap the benefit of the sa=
me ad spend to lure butts to seats and eyeballs to TV screens. But it=E2=80=
=99s a far more compressed window from multiplexes to subscription streamin=
g than is typically tolerated by theaters. If Netflix,
for instance, proposed such a release schedule for a wide release, the majo=
r chains would likely extend a double middle finger and refuse to play the =
movie.=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Amazon distribution chief Kevin Wilson notified the big chains in advance o=
f the short window on Red One. And, faced with a strike-hobbled slate of Ho=
llywood fare, they agreed to take the film, which has so far
grossed $94 million in North America=E2=80=94pretty poor, given its cost an=
d the full-freight marketing. Despite acquiescing, however, the theater own=
ers weren=E2=80=99t thrilled about this arrangement, per multiple sources, =
especially if it portends how Amazon will act in the future. Nor was Michae=
l O=E2=80=99Leary, the head of the National Association of Theatre Owners, =
the lobbying group for exhibition. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think that is a=
 sustainable model,=E2=80=9D O=E2=80=99Leary
told ( https://open.spotify.com/show/4uXizLZjslhw7nyDPocta2?utm_campaign=3D=
What+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F19%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27=
m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F19%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_so=
urce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) me this week. =E2=80=9CI=
 can tell you it=E2=80=99s not a sustainable model. It=E2=80=99s not one th=
at we would support.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Granted, Red One was in a somewhat unique situation. Originally greenlit fo=
r streaming, Amazon then followed industry sentiment and shifted toward the=
aters for big-budget
titles. That meant a November 15 theatrical release, bypassing premium vide=
o-on-demand, and going direct to Prime Video on December 12, just in time f=
or the Christmas deluge, putting it up against the Lindsay Lohan and Chad M=
ichael Murray holiday dreck on Netflix, the Hallmark/Lifetime fire hose of =
Bulgaria-shot cheapo fare, and Elf on whichever platform will pay Warner Br=
os. some quick cash. Against this competition, Red One has been huge. Not
a shock.=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But it is a cheat, and a big pivot from what the traditional studios are do=
ing. Universal, which was first to break the 45-day theatrical window durin=
g Covid, initially put movies on P.V.O.D. after 17 days, if they opened to =
less than $50 million (31 days for bigger movies), then to Peacock after 45=
 days. Now Uni typically holds movies a little longer, waiting 75 to 120 da=
ys
before going to Peacock. Movies like Conclave from Focus, its specialty lab=
el, still arrive on Peacock after around 45 to 60 days.

=C2=A0

Other studios use flexible formulas, usually based on how the films perform=
 in theaters. Warner Bros.=E2=80=99 Beetlejuice Beetlejuice, a hit in the U=
=2ES., appeared on P.V.O.D. after 33 da=
ys, then landed on Max after 92 days.=20=
Horizon: An American Saga: Part
One, which was, uh, not a hit, went to P.V.O.D. after just 19 days, but sti=
ll waited 57 days to premiere on Max. Disney, for its bigger movies, mainta=
ins a 60-day theatrical window before sending movies to P.V.O.D. or S.V.O.D=
=2E platforms.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Disney is the biggest theatrical player, and it also doesn=E2=80=99t market=
 any other windows until more than six weeks after the release in theaters.
That=E2=80=99s key, because moviegoers who use Fandango or other ticketing =
platforms will sometimes be presented with an option to buy a seat at their=
 local theater or a rental for the same movie when it=E2=80=99s available=
=E2=80=94often mere weeks or even days later. Given the ancillary costs and=
 hassles of a theater experience, it basically begs for a cost-benefit anal=
ysis=E2=80=94How much do I really want to see this movie now?=E2=80=94that=
=E2=80=99s not great for theaters, of course.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Anyway, for O=E2=80=99Leary and the theater owners, there=E2=80=99s a big d=
ifference between P.V.O.D. (the higher-priced, individual film rentals) and=
 electronic sell-through (iTunes and other film purchases)=E2=80=94both of =
which are premium offerings with relatively small reach=E2=80=94and the mas=
sive S.V.O.D. services, like Prime Video, which boasts more than 200 millio=
n customers worldwide, many of whom consider the platform =E2=80=9Cfree=E2=
=80=9D with Prime
shipping. For that reason, sending a movie to Prime Video after 27 days is =
much different than even, say, offering it to P.V.O.D. after 17 days. =E2=
=80=9CI had conversations last week with the folks at MGM-Amazon and have m=
ade it very clear that we understand the circumstances about Red One,=E2=80=
=9D O=E2=80=99Leary told me. =E2=80=9CBut as an industry, we can=E2=80=99t =
support something like a 25-day window where it goes directly to a streamin=
g service.=E2=80=9D (Amazon declined to comment on those talks.)

Lines in the Sand
-----------------

Okay, but what, exactly, can the theaters do about this? After all, Amazon =
would
argue that three weeks of exclusivity in theaters is better than zero weeks=
, and the $94 million Red One has generated domestically is money the theat=
ers would forgo if they drew an arbitrary line in the sand. Most movies hav=
e all but exhausted their earning potential after four weekends in theaters=
, anyway. And even if not, Red One remained on 3,000 screens last weekend d=
espite appearing on Prime Video, and it still generated $4.4 million in U.S=
=2E ticket sales. Would
it have grossed more if it wasn=E2=80=99t available at home? Maybe. But pro=
bably not much more.=C2=A0=C2=A0

