=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Question: Do you consider Amazon a friend =
or foe of movie
theaters? Gotta be a <em>friend</em>, right? For most of this year, Prime V=
ideo and its studio division have been positioning themselves as a savior o=
f sorts to the theatrical industry, with plans to release <em>dozens</em> o=
f big-budget movies in cinemas over the next few years. Amazon certainly pi=
tches its theater plans when it=E2=80=99s trying to lure projects from Netf=
lix and other buyers. And if you talk to theater executives, they=E2=80=99r=
e counting on Amazon=E2=80=99s ambitions to compensate for pullbacks
elsewhere, particularly in non-=E2=80=9Cevent=E2=80=9D films.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">But, man, Amazon is a huge question mark, one whose motives and am=
bitions will be a driving narrative of the movie business in 2025. Consider=
 what=E2=80=99s going on with <em>Red One</em>. Amazon MGM Studios has been=
 jumping up and down to declare the <strong>Dwayne Johnson</strong>-<strong=
>Chris Evans</strong> holiday movie the most viewed in the <em>history</em>=
 of
Prime Video. Not mentioned in those press releases: The $250 million Santa =
kidnapping extravaganza landed on the service just 27 days after a theatric=
al debut that was buoyed by a massive, $100 million marketing campaign. Tha=
t=E2=80=99s a dream for a film studio, which can reap the benefit of the sa=
me ad spend to lure butts to seats <em>and</em> eyeballs to TV screens. But=
 it=E2=80=99s a far more compressed window from multiplexes to subscription=
 streaming than is typically tolerated by theaters. If Netflix,
for instance, proposed such a release schedule for a wide release, the majo=
r chains would likely extend a double middle finger and refuse to play the =
movie.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Amazon distribution chief <strong>Ke=
vin Wilson</strong> notified the big chains in advance of the short window =
on <em>Red One</em>. And, faced with a strike-hobbled slate of Hollywood fa=
re, they agreed to take the film, which has so far
grossed $94 million in North America=E2=80=94pretty poor, given its cost an=
d the full-freight marketing. Despite acquiescing, however, the theater own=
ers weren=E2=80=99t thrilled about this arrangement, per multiple sources, =
especially if it portends how Amazon will act in the future. Nor was <stron=
g>Michael O=E2=80=99Leary</strong>, the head of the National Association of=
 Theatre Owners, the lobbying group for exhibition. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99=
t think that is a sustainable model,=E2=80=9D O=E2=80=99Leary
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
clJLZ0dUNHR6NUR0TmlMelFNazFDRGZCdz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9vcGVuLnNwb3RpZnk=
uY29tL3Nob3cvNHVYaXpMWmpzbGh3N255RFBvY3RhMj91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249V2hhdCtJJTI3bS=
tIZWFyaW5nKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkYxOSUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlb=
nQ9V2hhdCtJJTI3bStIZWFyaW5nKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkYxOSUyRjI0JTI5XHUw=
MDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHU=
wMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhND=
JhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo2OTg5OH0/4649ea22f2e30da4d3fb0711ad8bbd6d6c54cc6bc=
67f6b1b1be45e20a5990e0f" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;"=
>told</a> me this week. =E2=80=9CI can tell you it=E2=80=99s <em>not</em> a=
 sustainable model. It=E2=80=99s not one that we would support.=E2=80=9D</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">Granted, <em>Red One</em> was in a somewhat unique situat=
ion. Originally greenlit for streaming, Amazon then followed industry senti=
ment and shifted toward theaters for big-budget
titles. That meant a November 15 theatrical release, bypassing premium vide=
o-on-demand, and going direct to Prime Video on December 12, just in time f=
or the Christmas deluge, putting it up against the <strong>Lindsay Lohan</s=
trong> and <strong>Chad Michael Murray</strong> holiday dreck on Netflix, t=
he Hallmark/Lifetime fire hose of Bulgaria-shot cheapo fare, and <em>Elf</e=
m> on whichever platform will pay Warner Bros. some quick cash. Against thi=
s competition, <em>Red One</em> has been huge. Not
a shock.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But it <em>is</em> a cheat, and a =
big pivot from what the traditional studios are doing. Universal, which was=
 first to break the 45-day theatrical window during Covid, initially put mo=
vies on P.V.O.D. after 17 days, if they opened to less than $50 million (31=
 days for bigger movies), then to Peacock after 45 days. Now Uni typically =
holds movies a little longer, waiting 75 to 120 days
before going to Peacock. Movies like <em>Conclave</em> from Focus, its spec=
ialty label, still arrive on Peacock after around 45 to 60 days.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">Other studios use flexible formulas, usually based on how the fil=
ms perform in theaters. Warner Bros.=E2=80=99 <em>Beetlejuice Beetlejuice</=
em>, a hit in the U.S., appeared on P.V.O.D. after 33 days, then landed on =
Max after 92 days. <em>Horizon: An American Saga: Part
One</em>, which was, uh, <em>not</em> a hit, went to P.V.O.D. after just 19=
 days, but still waited 57 days to premiere on Max. Disney, for its bigger =
movies, maintains a 60-day theatrical window before sending movies to P.V.O=
=2ED. <em>or</em> S.V.O.D. platforms=
=2E=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Disney is the=
 biggest theatrical player, and it also doesn=E2=80=99t market any other wi=
ndows until more than six weeks after the release in theaters.
That=E2=80=99s key, because moviegoers who use Fandango or other ticketing =
platforms will sometimes be presented with an option to buy a seat at their=
 local theater <em>or</em> a rental for the same movie when it=E2=80=99s av=
ailable=E2=80=94often mere weeks or even days later. Given the ancillary co=
sts and hassles of a theater experience, it basically begs for a cost-benef=
it analysis=E2=80=94<em>How much do I really want to see this movie now?</e=
m>=E2=80=94that=E2=80=99s not great for theaters, of course.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;">Anyway, for O=E2=80=99Leary and the theater owners, there=E2=80=99s a=
 <em>big</em> difference between P.V.O.D. (the higher-priced, individual fi=
lm rentals) and electronic sell-through (iTunes and other film purchases)=
=E2=80=94both of which are premium offerings with relatively small reach=E2=
=80=94and the massive S.V.O.D. services, like Prime Video, which boasts mor=
e than 200 million customers worldwide, many of whom consider the platform =
=E2=80=9Cfree=E2=80=9D with Prime
shipping. For that reason, sending a movie to Prime Video after 27 days is =
<em>much</em> different than even, say, offering it to P.V.O.D. after 17 da=
ys. =E2=80=9CI had conversations last week with the folks at MGM-Amazon and=
 have made it very clear that we understand the circumstances about <em>Red=
 One</em>,=E2=80=9D O=E2=80=99Leary told me. =E2=80=9CBut as an industry, w=
e can=E2=80=99t support something like a 25-day window where it goes direct=
ly to a streaming service.=E2=80=9D (Amazon declined to comment on those ta=
lks.)</p></div>
