tes that it saw little to no cannibalization on <em>Twisters</em>, <em>Desp=
icable Me 4</em>, and <em>The Wild Robot</em>, all of which did decent busi=
ness in theaters even while available to rent or own. At the same time, the=
 P.V.O.D. window has accounted for $1.5 billion in consumer spend on
Universal movies since the model was retooled during Covid, according to th=
e studio. That money helps cushion the blow from flops <em>and</em> pay for=
 more potential blockbusters=E2=80=A6 to play in theaters.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">But that=E2=80=99s kinda not the point, at least not when it comes to t=
he widely available S.V.O.D. platforms. Short windows may not cannibalize i=
ndividual titles like <em>Red One</em>, but they <em>train</em>
audiences to expect speedy delivery to the streamers, which in turn depress=
es demand for theatrical movies <em>in toto</em>. That was a general lesson=
 of Netflix and all the Covid-era experimentation, and it=E2=80=99s why the=
se non-Netflix studios are maintaining their longer S.V.O.D. windows for mo=
vies that have a shot at a theatrical audience. (I=E2=80=99m excluding tiny=
 indies here=E2=80=A6 and don=E2=80=99t get me started on Lionsgate and its=
 aggressive P.V.O.D. windowing.) Pay a high price for movies in theaters, p=
ay a
<em>higher</em> price for movies on demand a few weeks later, or pay only y=
our S.V.O.D. subscription price when the movie arrives there way later: Tha=
t seems to be a sweet spot compromise for meaningful theatrical releases th=
at both sides can live with.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">So, if A=
