t this year. <strong>Mike Hopkins</strong> and <strong>Jen Salke</strong>, =
the top Amazon content executives, are expected to attend CinemaCon in Marc=
h, where Amazon MGM will present to theater owners for the first
time and explain why the world=E2=80=99s largest digital retailer <em>reall=
y</em> cares about the brick-and-mortar theater experience. It=E2=80=99ll b=
e interesting to see.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Apple, on the other hand, i=
sn=E2=80=99t even pretending to care about movie theaters anymore. O=E2=80=
=99Leary still calls Apple a =E2=80=9Cpartner,=E2=80=9D though he=E2=80=99s=
 as nervous as the rest of his members about this summer=E2=80=99s move to =
scrap the theatrical release for
<strong>George Clooney</strong> and <strong>Brad Pitt</strong>=E2=80=99s <e=
m>Wolfs</em>. =E2=80=9CWhen decisions are made that impact the theatrical w=
indow after the movie is somewhere in the process, that=E2=80=99s not a pos=
itive and constructive way to move forward,=E2=80=9D O=E2=80=99Leary told m=
e. =E2=80=9CSo that has certainly been conveyed. But I also think that they=
 are putting a lot of time and energy and resources into <em>F1</em>.=E2=80=
=9D That=E2=80=99s true, but after that release via Warner Bros. next summe=
r, what then?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Now =
that the Hollywood studios have, for the most part, reprioritized theaters =
(unless you=E2=80=99re <strong>Clint Eastwood</strong>), and Netflix has de=
clared itself a platform for pricey TV movies (unless you=E2=80=99re <stron=
g>Greta Gerwig</strong>), windowing remains the real battleground. Amazon h=
asn=E2=80=99t articulated its general theaters-to-Prime Video policy, but i=
f the cheerleading for the <em>Red One</em> numbers is any indication, the
strategy will be aggressively weighted toward using theaters to power strea=
ming as quickly as possible.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">For multiplex =
owners, the last thing you want is for the theatrical release to become a q=
uasi-marketing play for streaming=E2=80=94something designed only to reimbu=
rse prints and advertising expenses and provide an imprimatur of =E2=80=9Ct=
heatricality=E2=80=9D in service of the home video release, like how film
festivals and their fancy logos are leveraged by prestige movies to connote=
 an aura of quality.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Amazon may be positioning itself as the frien=
dly neighborhood streamer to the theater industry, but like Netflix and App=
le, it ultimately cares only about its global streaming ambitions, not its =
ability to make money in a declining business. And that incentive isn=E2=80=
=99t changing, despite the =E2=80=9Ccommitment=E2=80=9D to the multiplex. T=
he
question is whether Amazon can leverage theaters to achieve its actual goal=
s more than the theaters can leverage Amazon to serve theirs, and what vict=
ory looks like for both sides.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
